In order to achieve the desired functionality in an Ant Design table with React, you can use rowSelection object and the getCheckboxProps function to control the disabled state of the checkboxes.

Here's a sample code to demonstrate the approach:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Table } from 'antd';

const columns = [
  {
    title: 'Bank',
    dataIndex: 'bank',
    key: 'bank',
  },
  {
    title: 'Name',
    dataIndex: 'name',
    key: 'name',
  },
];

const data = [
  {
    key: '1',
    bank: 'Agricola',
    name: 'John Smith',
  },
  {
    key: '2',
    bank: 'Other',
    name: 'James Brown',
  },
];

const App = () => {
  const [selectedBank, setSelectedBank] = useState('');

  const rowSelection = {
    onChange: (selectedRowKeys, selectedRows) => {
      if (selectedRows.length > 0) {
        setSelectedBank(selectedRows[0].bank);
      } else {
        setSelectedBank('');
      }
    },
    getCheckboxProps: (record) => ({
      disabled: selectedBank !== '' && record.bank !== selectedBank,
    }),
  };

  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Table
        rowSelection={{
          type: 'checkbox',
          ...rowSelection,
        }}
        columns={columns}
        dataSource={data}
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this code:

1. We've defined a state named `selectedBank` to keep track of the bank name that is selected.
2. We've created a `rowSelection` object containing the onChange and getCheckboxProps functions to control the table selection.
3. onChange function updates the `selectedBank` state depending on the rows selected.
4. getCheckboxProps function disables checkboxes for rows that don't match the selected bank.
5. In the Table component, we've used the `rowSelection` object to control the selection behavior.

With this setup, when you select a row, other rows with different bank names will become disabled.

To modify the code so that you can select multiple records with different bank names but only disable others when selecting a record with bank == "Agricola", you need to change the logic inside the `onChange` and `getCheckboxProps` functions. Here's the updated code:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Table } from 'antd';

const columns = [
  {
    title: 'Bank',
    dataIndex: 'bank',
    key: 'bank',
  },
  {
    title: 'Name',
    dataIndex: 'name',
    key: 'name',
  },
];

const data = [
  {
    key: '1',
    bank: 'Agricola',
    name: 'John Smith',
  },
  {
    key: '2',
    bank: 'Other',
    name: 'James Brown',
  },
];

const App = () => {
  const [selectedAgricola, setSelectedAgricola] = useState(false);

  const rowSelection = {
    onChange: (selectedRowKeys, selectedRows) => {
      if (selectedRows.some(row => row.bank === 'Agricola')) {
        setSelectedAgricola(true);
      } else {
        setSelectedAgricola(false);
      }
    },
    getCheckboxProps: (record) => ({
      disabled: selectedAgricola && record.bank !== 'Agricola',
    }),
  };

  return (
    <div className="App">
      <Table
        rowSelection={{
          type: 'checkbox',
          ...rowSelection,
        }}
        columns={columns}
        dataSource={data}
      />
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this updated code:

1. We've renamed the state to `selectedAgricola` to indicate whether a record with bank == "Agricola" is selected or not.
2. In the `onChange` function, we check if any of the selected rows has bank == "Agricola" and set `selectedAgricola` accordingly.
3. In the `getCheckboxProps` function, we only disable checkboxes for rows that don't have bank == "Agricola" if `selectedAgricola` is true.

Now, you can select multiple records with different bank names, but once you select a record with bank == "Agricola", the other rows with different bank names will get disabled.
